# UX & Accessibility Rules

## Design System

- **4px baseline** - All spacing uses 4px increments (4px, 8px, 12px, 16px, 20px, 24px)
- **Tailwind CSS v4** - Use utility classes, follow design tokens
- **Consistent patterns** - Reuse UI patterns across features
- **Responsive design** - Mobile-first approach

## User Experience

### States
- **Every screen has loading/empty/error/success states** - All screens must handle all four states
- **Loading states** - Show loading indicators for async operations
  - Use skeletons, spinners, or progress indicators
  - Provide context about what is loading
- **Empty states** - Provide helpful empty state messages
  - Explain why the screen is empty
  - Provide actionable next steps when appropriate
- **Error states** - Clear, actionable error messages
  - Explain what went wrong
  - Provide recovery options when possible
- **Success states** - Confirm successful actions
  - Provide clear feedback for completed actions
  - Guide users to next steps when appropriate

### Interactions
- **Feedback** - Provide immediate feedback for user actions
- **Progressive disclosure** - Show information progressively
- **Error prevention** - Validate inputs before submission
- **Confirmation** - Confirm destructive actions

### Writing
- **Clear and concise** - Use plain language
- **Instructional** - Guide users through tasks
- **Consistent tone** - Professional but friendly
- **Action-oriented** - Use active voice

## Accessibility (WCAG 2.2 AA)

- **WCAG 2.2 AA baseline** - All features must meet WCAG 2.2 AA standards
- This is the minimum accessibility requirement for all UI components

### Semantic HTML
- **Semantic HTML first, ARIA only if needed** - Use proper HTML elements before ARIA
- Prefer native HTML elements and attributes over ARIA
- Only add ARIA when semantic HTML cannot express the meaning
- **Proper heading hierarchy** - Use h1-h6 in order
- **Landmark regions** - Use nav, main, aside, etc.
- **Form labels** - All inputs must have associated labels

### Keyboard Navigation
- **Keyboard accessible** - All interactive elements accessible via keyboard
- **Focus order** - Logical tab order
- **Focus indicators** - Visible focus states
- **Skip links** - Provide skip to main content links

### Screen Readers
- **ARIA labels** - Use when semantic HTML isn't sufficient
- **ARIA attributes** - Use aria-describedby, aria-labelledby appropriately
- **Live regions** - Use aria-live for dynamic content
- **Test with screen readers** - Verify with actual screen reader software

### Visual Accessibility
- **Color contrast** - Meet WCAG 2.2 AA standards (4.5:1 for text, 3:1 for UI)
- **Color independence** - Don't rely solely on color to convey information
- **Text alternatives** - All images must have descriptive alt attributes
- **Focus management** - Manage focus for modals, dialogs, and dynamic content

### Error Handling
- **Error messages** - Clear, actionable error messages
- **Error association** - Associate errors with form fields (aria-describedby)
- **User-friendly messages** - Errors should be clear and actionable
- **Type-safe errors** - Use discriminated unions for error states

## Performance

- **Fast initial load** - Optimize bundle size
- **Smooth interactions** - 60fps animations
- **Progressive enhancement** - Works without JavaScript
- **Image optimization** - Use Next.js Image component
